Bike Share Project

Joseph Ramaswami

2022-10-31

Introduction

Cyclistic is a bike sharing company. They have three different pricing plans: single day, full-day pass, and annual membership. Users of the first two plans are referred to as casual riders, the last as members. Cyclistics financial analysts determined that annual memberships are more profitable. Lily Moreno, CEO of Cyclistic, would like to know how do annual members and casual riders use Cyclistic bikes differently?

Data

Source

The data consists of observations about bike trips for four quarters starting in Q2 2019 and ending in Q1 2020. This data is public data available under this license. It can be downloaded from the following index page. The following four data files are used:

Data Files
File Names
Divvy_Trips_2019_Q2.zip
Divvy_Trips_2019_Q3.zip
Divvy_Trips_2019_Q4.zip
Divvy_Trips_2020_Q1.zip

Data Preparation

The data available is inconsistent between the four files. The data will be standardized to contain the following variables:

Data Dictionary
Variable Datatype Description
ride_id character An unique id for a given ride.
rideable_type character Before 2020 this was the id for the bike ridden. After 2020 it is the type of bike ridden.
started_at date-time Date and time the ride started.
ended_at date-time Date and time the ride ended.
start_station_name character Name of station where ride started.
start_station_id number Unique id for station where ride started.
end_station_name character Name of station where ride ended.
end_station_id number Unique id for station where ride ended.
member_casual character Type of rider: ‘member’ or ‘casual’.

There are several steps required to clean the data.

  1. Variables in files from 2019 are renamed to be consistent with those in the 2020 data file.

  2. ride_id and rideable_type in 2019 data files are converted into character data so that they can stack with the new character based variables used in data from 2020 onward.

  3. There are observations 130 trips where started_at is after ended_at. These observations will be removed.

  4. The member_casual data must be fixed. In the 2019 data files, the member_casual variable had values of “Subscriber” and “Customer”; these will be replaced with “member” and “casual”, respectively. This is consistent with data gathered from 2020 onward.

  5. A single observation has missing values for the end_station_name and the end_station_id; this observation will be dropped.

  6. The specifications for this project mention bicycles removed for quality control reasons. They have starting or ending station names of “HQ QR” and there are 3768 observations that will be removed.

The resulting clean data set consists of 3876041 observations.

Analysis

Trip start day by rider type.

Overall, member take more trips then casual users. However, we can see from the figure below that casual members appear to take more of their trips on the weekend, where members take the more trips on weekdays. This may indicate that members purchase membership because they are commuting by bicycle and are therefore more regular users.

Trip start time by weekday by rider type.

The figure below supports the hypothesis that members are bicycle commuters as we can see an increase in the number of trips in during morning rush hours and a corresponding increase during afternoon rush hours. This trend is not visible in casual riders who see an increase throughout the day into the afternoon, followed by decreases into the night hours. The same trend is apparent in member riders on the weekend.

Duration of ride by rider type

Summary Statistics for Duration in Seconds by Rider Type
Member Type Mean Min Q1 Median Q3 Max IQR
casual 3552.7502 2 910 1546 2715 9387024 1805
member 849.9909 1 362 589 971 9056634 609

As indicated by the table and figure above, it appears that casual riders tend to have rides of longer duration. This may support the hypothesis that members are bicycle commuters. A possible explanation are that members are not taking extended trips because of the necessity to arrive at work or get home in a timely manner.

Percent of rides by rider type by station.

As seen in the above tables, there are several stations where there is a greater than 1% difference by rider type in the percentage of rides that start or end at the given station. However, more statistical studies should be undertaken to determine if the differences are significant.

Supplementary Analysis

Data collected in 2020 includes latitude and longitude for the starting and ending points of each trip. Though a limited sample, I thought it worth looking at the extra data for any possible insights.

Start and end location by rider type

Geographically, there does not appear to be any significant difference between where members and casual riders start or end their trips.

Analysis Summary

  1. As indicated by the days a ride starts and the time of day a ride starts, members appear to be bicycle commuters.

  2. Casual riders appear to take longer trips than members.

  3. There may be some differences in the start and end stations used by members and casual riders but the lack of geographical differences by latitude and longitude indicate that these differences are probably negligible.

Recommendations

  1. I think that Cyclistic should target bicycle commuters that are still casual riders in an effort to convert them into members.

  2. It might be possible to partner with large companies in the area to make their employees aware of the possibility of bicycle commuting.

  3. In addition, perhaps some kind of advertising at bike stations during rush hours would also be opportune.
